# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: prores-codec
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:prores-codec/apple-prores] ProRes is a line of intermediate codecs, which means they are intended for use during video editing, and not for practical end-user viewing.
[src:prores-codec/apple-prores] This is achieved by only using intra-frame compression, where each frame is stored independently and can be decoded with no dependencies on other frames.
[src:prores-codec/apple-prores] The benefit of an intermediate codec is that it offers excellent random access performance in post-production applications, and retains higher quality than end-user codecs while still requiring much less expensive disk systems compared to uncompressed video.
[src:prores-codec/apple-prores] It is comparable to Avid's DNxHD codec or CineForm which offer similar bitrates and are also intended to be used as intermediate codecs.
[src:prores-codec/apple-prores] ProRes is a DCT scalar based intra-frame-only codec and is therefore simpler to decode than distribution-oriented formats like H.264.
[src:prores-codec/apple-prores] In 2018 Apple added a new "ProRes RAW" (compressed Bayer filter) to Final Cut Pro X, after Blackmagic Design implemented compressed Bayer as "CinemaDNG 3:1" and "CinemaDNG 4:1" in their cameras and DaVinci Resolve.
[src:prores-codec/apple-prores] ProRes supports different data rates and different resolutions.
[src:prores-codec/apple-prores] All ProRes422-variants use chroma subsampling of 4:2:2 at 10-bit color depth.
[src:prores-codec/apple-prores] ProRes 4444 and 4444 XQ samples color in the 4:4:4 schema with a color depth of 10 or 12 bits, and can optionally include an alpha channel.
[src:prores-codec/apple-prores] ProRes 4444 was introduced with Final Cut Studio (2009) as another in the company's line of intermediate codecs for editing material but not for final delivery.
[src:prores-codec/apple-prores] It shares many features with other, 422, codecs of Apple's ProRes family but provides better quality than 422 HQ in color detail.
[src:prores-codec/apple-prores] It has a target data rate of approximately 330 Mbit/s for 4:4:4 sources at 1920x1080 and 29.97 fps.
[src:prores-codec/apple-prores] ProRes 4444 XQ was introduced with Final Cut Pro X version 10.1.2 in June 2014.
[src:prores-codec/apple-prores] It has a target data rate of approximately 500 Mbit/s for 4:4:4 sources at 1920x1080 and 29.97 fps, and requires OS X v10.8 (Mountain Lion) or later.
[src:prores-codec/apple-prores] In April 2018 Apple released ProRes RAW.
[src:prores-codec/apple-prores] It is built upon the same technology as other ProRes codecs, but is directly applied to the raw data coming from the sensor, thus delaying the debayering process to the post-production stage.
[src:prores-codec/apple-prores] ProRes RAW therefore aims at quality and better color reproduction, rather than performance.
[src:prores-codec/apple-prores] Apple ProRes RAW is available in LUMIX cameras, Nikon cameras (Z9, Z8, Z6iii), Sony Alpha FX3 via Atomos Ninja V, and as of September 2025, in the Apple iPhone 17 Pro and ProMax.
[src:prores-codec/apple-prores] ProRes RAW is a 16 bit uncompressed video format in .mov.
[src:prores-codec/apple-prores] In the Sony FX3 and the Atomos Ninja V, ProRes Raw records in 16 bit and compresses in 12 bit for color data.
[src:prores-codec/apple-prores] ProRes RAW codec is natively available in Adobe Premiere Pro, Adobe After Effects, Assimilate Scratch, Apple Final Cut Pro and Davinci Resolve.
[src:prores-codec/apple-prores] On 28 August 2008, Apple introduced a free ProRes QuickTime Decoder for both Mac and Windows that allows playback of ProRes files through QuickTime.
[src:prores-codec/apple-prores] On 15 September 2011, FFmpeg introduced a free decoder for ProRes 422 for libavcodec.
[src:prores-codec/apple-prores] FFmbc, a fork of FFmpeg customized for broadcast and professional usage, supports ProRes 422 and 4444 files.
[src:prores-codec/apple-prores] On 1 October 2011, JCodec introduced an open source (FreeBSD License) pure Java decoder for ProRes 422, a translation of the FFmpeg version.
[src:prores-codec/apple-prores] Installing Final Cut Pro will install the ProRes codecs for encoding files on macOS.
[src:prores-codec/apple-prores] Without Final Cut Pro installed, QuickTime Player can also be used to capture ProRes 422 video from any compatible attached camera, using the "Maximum" quality setting when producing a Movie Recording.
[src:prores-codec/apple-prores] Apple released ProRes bundled with other pro codecs as a download for users with "qualifying copies of Final Cut Pro, Motion, or Compressor" installed, for OS X with QuickTime 7.6 and newer.
[src:prores-codec/apple-prores] At the April 2010 NAB Show, Digital Video Systems launched the first Windows 7 platform with the ability to encode to all the varieties of Apple ProRes at speeds far faster than real time on their Clipster product.
[src:prores-codec/apple-prores] On March 31, 2011, Telestream added support for ProRes encoding on Windows systems with Episode Engine, Vantage, and FlipFactory as a free upgrade to the current versions of these products.
[src:prores-codec/apple-prores] The system must be running on Windows Server 2008 and be able to support this feature.
[src:prores-codec/apple-prores] ProRes video capturing and output to tape is available in Telestream's Pipeline network encoder.
[src:prores-codec/apple-prores] On 29 October 2011, FFmpeg introduced a free encoder, enabling ProRes 422 encoding on all FFmpeg supported platforms.
[src:prores-codec/apple-prores] On 1 November 2011, JCodec introduced an open source (BSD License) pure Java encoder for ProRes 422.
[src:prores-codec/apple-prores] At the April 2012 NAB Show, Brevity introduced a customized algorithm for the accelerated transport and encoding of ProRes files.
[src:prores-codec/apple-prores] The Arri Alexa has a built-in ProRes recording unit for its 1080p and 2K video streams, supporting ProRes 4444 and all ProRes 422 versions.
[src:prores-codec/apple-prores] At NAB 2012, Blackmagic announced ProRes recording support for their HyperDeck SSD recorders as well as onboard recording on the Blackmagic Cinema Camera, and Brevity announced a GPU-based ProRes transcoder with simultaneous accelerated file transport.
[src:prores-codec/apple-prores] In 2013 Blackmagic Design released the Blackmagic Cinema Camera that record in RAW and ProRes files directly in camera 4:2:2 10-bit.
[src:prores-codec/apple-prores] In 2013 Convergent Design introduced their Odyssey7 and Odyssey7Q monitor/recorders that can record in Apple ProRes 422 (HQ) and are certified by Apple.
[src:prores-codec/apple-prores] In 2014 Atomos introduced their latest advanced recorder Shogun that can record 4K in Apple ProRes.
[src:prores-codec/apple-prores] In 2015 AJA introduced the CION production camera that can capture 4K/UltraHD/2K/HD to all Apple ProRes 422 formats as well as Apple ProRes 4444 in 12-bit.
[src:prores-codec/apple-prores] In 2016 Blackmagic Design released UrsaMini 4.6k that can capture from 4.6k to HD in all Apple ProRes flavor from Proxy to 4444 in 12-bit.
[src:prores-codec/apple-prores] In 2018/2019 Blackmagic Design released Pocket Cinema Camera 4K that can capture 4k/UltraHD/1080p in all Apple ProRes 422 formats.
[src:prores-codec/apple-prores] In 2019 Mac Pro introduced a new "Apple Afterburner" card as an optional component to accelerate ProRes and ProRes RAW decoding.
[src:prores-codec/apple-prores] In 2021, Apple announced the iPhone 13 Pro, with ProRes encoding/decoding using its built-in camera app alongside its recent addition of DNG raw photos (DNG v5.1) on the 12 Pro Models.
[src:prores-codec/apple-prores] ProRes encoding can be performed at up to 3840 × 2160 30p ProRes HQ with Dolby Vision HDR color profiles on models with at least 256 GB of storage, while the 128 GB model will be limited to 1080p 30p with its built-in camera application.
[src:prores-codec/apple-prores] In 2023, Apple announced the iPhone 15 Pro, which added the ability to shoot ProRes in the Apple Log format, as well as the ability to shoot ProRes footage at up to 3840 x 2160 60p to an external drive via the USB-C port from the built-in camera application.
[src:prores-codec/apple-prores] In 2021, Apple announced the Apple M1 Pro and M1 Max, variants of the Apple M1 system on a chip containing, among other new features, hardware ProRes encoding and decoding acceleration.
[src:prores-codec/apple-prores] In February 2022, Panasonic released the Lumix GH6 mirrorless camera which has the ability to record 5.7K video in ProRes 422 HQ.
[src:prores-codec/apple-prores] On June 6, 2022, Apple announced the Apple M2 with 8K ProRes hardware decoding and encoding acceleration.
[src:prores-codec/apple-prores] On January 17, 2023, Apple announced the Apple M2 Pro and M2 Max with 8K ProRes hardware decoding and encoding acceleration.
[src:prores-codec/apple-prores] On October 30, 2023, Apple announced the Apple M3 series of chips with 8K ProRes hardware decoding and encoding acceleration.
[src:prores-codec/apple-prores] Lasergraphics motion picture film scanning systems include support for output to ProRes 4444 HQ/XQ, ProRes 422, and others.
[src:prores-codec/apple-prores] The ProRes codec was awarded an Engineering Emmy Award in 2020 for "Outstanding Achievement in Technology".
[src:prores-codec/chroma-subsampling] It is used in many video and still image encoding schemes – both analog and digital – including in JPEG encoding.
[src:prores-codec/chroma-subsampling] Digital signals are often compressed to reduce file size and save transmission time.
[src:prores-codec/chroma-subsampling] Since the human visual system is much more sensitive to variations in brightness than color, a video system can be optimized by devoting more bandwidth to the luma component (usually denoted Y'), than to the color difference components **Cb** and **Cr**.
[src:prores-codec/chroma-subsampling] In compressed images, for example, the 4:2:2 Y'CbCr scheme requires two-thirds the bandwidth of non-subsampled "4:4:4" R'G'B'.
[src:prores-codec/chroma-subsampling] This reduction results in almost no visual difference as perceived by the viewer.
[src:prores-codec/chroma-subsampling] The human vision system processes color information (hue and colorfulness) at about a third of the resolution of luminance (lightness/darkness information in an image).
[src:prores-codec/chroma-subsampling] Therefore it is possible to sample color information at a lower resolution while maintaining good image quality.
[src:prores-codec/chroma-subsampling] This is achieved by encoding RGB image data into a composite black and white image, with separated color difference data (chroma).
[src:prores-codec/chroma-subsampling] For example with $Y'C_{b}C_{r}$ , gamma encoded $R'G'B'$ components are weighted and then summed together to create the luma $Y'$ component.
[src:prores-codec/chroma-subsampling] The color difference components are created by subtracting two of the weighted $R'G'B'$ components from the third.
[src:prores-codec/chroma-subsampling] A variety of filtering methods can be used to limit the resolution.
[src:prores-codec/chroma-subsampling] Gamma encoded luma $Y'$ should not be confused with linear luminance Y .
[src:prores-codec/chroma-subsampling] The presence of gamma encoding is denoted with the prime symbol ' .
[src:prores-codec/chroma-subsampling] Gamma-correcting electro-optical transfer functions (EOTF) are used due to the nonlinear response of human vision.
[src:prores-codec/chroma-subsampling] The use of gamma improves perceived signal-to-noise in analogue systems, and allows for more efficient data encoding in digital systems.
[src:prores-codec/chroma-subsampling] This encoding uses more levels for darker colors than for lighter ones, accommodating human vision sensitivity.
[src:prores-codec/chroma-subsampling] The subsampling scheme is commonly expressed as a three-part ratio *J*:*a*:*b* (e.g.
[src:prores-codec/chroma-subsampling] 4:2:2) or four parts, if alpha channel is present (e.g.
[src:prores-codec/chroma-subsampling] 4:2:2:4), that describe the number of luminance and chrominance samples in a conceptual region that is *J* pixels wide and 2 pixels high.
[src:prores-codec/chroma-subsampling] This notation is not valid for all combinations and has exceptions, e.g.
[src:prores-codec/chroma-subsampling] 4:1:0 (where the height of the region is not 2 pixels, but 4 pixels, so if 8 bits per component are used, the media would be 9 bits per pixel) and 4:2:1.
[src:prores-codec/chroma-subsampling] The mapping examples given are only theoretical and for illustration.
[src:prores-codec/chroma-subsampling] Also the diagram does not indicate any chroma filtering, which should be applied to avoid aliasing.
[src:prores-codec/chroma-subsampling] To calculate required bandwidth factor relative to 4:4:4 (or 4:4:4:4), one needs to sum all the factors and divide the result by 12 (or 16, if alpha is present).
[src:prores-codec/chroma-subsampling] Each of the three Y'CbCr components has the same sample rate, thus there is no chroma subsampling.
[src:prores-codec/chroma-subsampling] This scheme is sometimes used in high-end film scanners and cinematic post-production.
[src:prores-codec/chroma-subsampling] "4:4:4" may instead be wrongly referring to R'G'B' color space, which implicitly also does not have any chroma subsampling (except in JPEG R'G'B' can be subsampled).
[src:prores-codec/chroma-subsampling] Formats such as HDCAM SR can record 4:4:4 R'G'B' over dual-link HD-SDI.
[src:prores-codec/chroma-subsampling] The two chroma components are sampled at half the horizontal sample rate of luma: the horizontal chroma resolution is halved.
[src:prores-codec/chroma-subsampling] This reduces the bandwidth of an uncompressed video signal by one-third, which means for 8 bit per component without alpha (24 bit per pixel) only 16 bits are enough, as in NV16.
[src:prores-codec/chroma-subsampling] In 4:1:1 chroma subsampling, the horizontal color resolution is quartered, and the bandwidth is halved compared to no chroma subsampling.
[src:prores-codec/chroma-subsampling] Initially, 4:1:1 chroma subsampling of the DV format was not considered to be broadcast quality and was only acceptable for low-end and consumer applications.
[src:prores-codec/chroma-subsampling] However, DV-based formats (some of which use 4:1:1 chroma subsampling) have been used professionally in electronic news gathering and in playout servers.
[src:prores-codec/chroma-subsampling] DV has also been sporadically used in feature films and in digital cinematography.
[src:prores-codec/chroma-subsampling] However, in most equipment, especially cheap TV sets and VHS/Betamax VCRs, the chroma channels have only the 0.5 MHz bandwidth for both **Cr** and **Cb** (or equivalently for I/Q).
[src:prores-codec/chroma-subsampling] Thus the DV system actually provides a superior color bandwidth compared to the best composite analog specifications for NTSC, despite having only 1/4 of the chroma bandwidth of a "full" digital signal.
[src:prores-codec/chroma-subsampling] In 4:2:0, the horizontal sampling is doubled compared to 4:1:1, but as the **Cb** and **Cr** channels are only sampled on each alternate line in this scheme, the vertical resolution is halved.
[src:prores-codec/chroma-subsampling] This fits reasonably well with the PAL color encoding system, since this has only half the vertical chrominance resolution of NTSC.
[src:prores-codec/chroma-subsampling] It would also fit extremely well with the SECAM color encoding system, since like that format, 4:2:0 only stores and transmits one color channel per line (the other channel being recovered from the previous line).
[src:prores-codec/chroma-subsampling] However, little equipment has actually been produced that outputs a SECAM analogue video signal.
[src:prores-codec/chroma-subsampling] In general, SECAM territories either have to use a PAL-capable display or a transcoder to convert the PAL signal to SECAM for display.
[src:prores-codec/chroma-subsampling] There are four main variants of 4:2:0 schemes, having different horizontal and vertical sampling relative to the 2×2 "square" of the original input size.
[src:prores-codec/chroma-subsampling] With interlaced material, 4:2:0 chroma subsampling can result in motion artifacts if it is implemented the same way as for progressive material.
[src:prores-codec/chroma-subsampling] The luma samples are derived from separate time intervals, while the chroma samples would be derived from both time intervals.
[src:prores-codec/chroma-subsampling] It is this difference that can result in motion artifacts.
[src:prores-codec/chroma-subsampling] The MPEG-2 standard allows for an alternate interlaced sampling scheme, where 4:2:0 is applied to each field (not both fields at once).
[src:prores-codec/chroma-subsampling] This solves the problem of motion artifacts, reduces the vertical chroma resolution by half, and can introduce comb-like artifacts in the image.
[src:prores-codec/chroma-subsampling] The moving text has some motion blur applied to it.
[src:prores-codec/chroma-subsampling] 4:2:0 **progressive** sampling applied to moving *interlaced* material.
[src:prores-codec/chroma-subsampling] The chroma leads and trails the moving text.
[src:prores-codec/chroma-subsampling] 4:2:0 **interlaced** sampling applied to moving *interlaced* material.
[src:prores-codec/chroma-subsampling] In the 4:2:0 interlaced scheme, however, vertical resolution of the chroma is roughly halved, since the chroma samples effectively describe an area 2 samples wide by 4 samples tall instead of 2×2.
[src:prores-codec/chroma-subsampling] As well, the spatial displacement between both fields can result in the appearance of comb-like chroma artifacts.
[src:prores-codec/chroma-subsampling] 4:2:0 **progressive** sampling applied to a still image.
[src:prores-codec/chroma-subsampling] 4:2:0 **interlaced** sampling applied to a still image.
[src:prores-codec/chroma-subsampling] If the interlaced material is to be de-interlaced, the comb-like chroma artifacts (from 4:2:0 interlaced sampling) can be removed by blurring the chroma vertically.
[src:prores-codec/chroma-subsampling] This ratio is possible, and some codecs support it, but it is not widely used.
[src:prores-codec/chroma-subsampling] This ratio uses half of the vertical and one-fourth the horizontal color resolutions, with only one-eighth of the bandwidth of the maximum color resolutions used.
[src:prores-codec/chroma-subsampling] Uncompressed video in this format with 8-bit quantization uses 10 bytes for every macropixel (which is 4×2 pixels) or 10 bit for every pixel.
[src:prores-codec/chroma-subsampling] It has the equivalent chrominance bandwidth of a PAL-I or PAL-M signal decoded with a delay line decoder, and still very much superior to NTSC.
[src:prores-codec/chroma-subsampling] Used by Sony in their HDCAM High Definition recorders (not HDCAM SR).
[src:prores-codec/chroma-subsampling] In the horizontal dimension, luma is sampled horizontally at three quarters of the full HD sampling rate – 1440 samples per row instead of 1920.
[src:prores-codec/chroma-subsampling] Chroma is sampled at 480 samples per row, a third of the luma sampling rate.
[src:prores-codec/chroma-subsampling] In the vertical dimension, both luma and chroma are sampled at the full HD sampling rate (1080 samples vertically).
[src:prores-codec/chroma-subsampling] A number of legacy schemes allow different subsampling factors in Cb and Cr, similar to how a different amount of bandwidth is allocated to the two chroma values in broadcast systems such as CCIR System M.
[src:prores-codec/chroma-subsampling] These schemes are not expressible in *J:a:b* notation.
[src:prores-codec/chroma-subsampling] Instead, they adopt a *Y:Cb:Cr* notation, with each part describing the amount of resolution for the corresponding component.
[src:prores-codec/chroma-subsampling] It is unspecified whether the resolution reduction happens in the horizontal or vertical direction.
[src:prores-codec/chroma-subsampling] Original image without color subsampling.
[src:prores-codec/chroma-subsampling] Note the bleeding in lightness near the borders.
[src:prores-codec/chroma-subsampling] Chroma subsampling suffers from two main types of artifacts, causing degradation more noticeable than intended where colors change abruptly.
[src:prores-codec/chroma-subsampling] Gamma-corrected signals like Y'CbCr have an issue where chroma errors "bleed" into luma.
[src:prores-codec/chroma-subsampling] In those signals, a low chroma actually makes a color appear less bright than one with equivalent luma.
[src:prores-codec/chroma-subsampling] As a result, when a saturated color blends with an unsaturated or complementary color, a loss of luminance occurs at the border.
[src:prores-codec/chroma-subsampling] This can be seen in the example between magenta and green.
[src:prores-codec/chroma-subsampling] This issue persists in HDR video where gamma is generalized into a transfer function "EOTF".
[src:prores-codec/chroma-subsampling] A steeper EOTF shows a stronger luminance loss.
[src:prores-codec/chroma-subsampling] 2020 defines a "constant luminance" Yc'CbcCrc, which is calculated from linear RGB components and then gamma-encoded.
[src:prores-codec/chroma-subsampling] This version does not suffer from the luminance loss by design.
[src:prores-codec/chroma-subsampling] Another artifact that can occur with chroma subsampling is that out-of-gamut colors can occur upon chroma reconstruction.
[src:prores-codec/chroma-subsampling] Suppose the image consisted of alternating 1-pixel red and black lines and the subsampling omitted the chroma for the black pixels.
[src:prores-codec/chroma-subsampling] Chroma from the red pixels will be reconstructed onto the black pixels, causing the new pixels to have positive red and *negative* green and blue values.
[src:prores-codec/chroma-subsampling] As displays cannot output negative light (negative light does not exist), these negative values will effectively be clipped, and the resulting luma value will be too high.
[src:prores-codec/chroma-subsampling] Other sub-sampling filters (especially the averaging "box") have a similar issue that is harder to make a simple example out of.
[src:prores-codec/chroma-subsampling] Similar artifacts arise in the less artificial example of gradation near a fairly sharp red/black boundary.
[src:prores-codec/chroma-subsampling] It is possible for the decoder to deal with out-of-gamut colors by considering how much chroma a given luma value can hold and distribute it into the 4:4:4 intermediate accordingly, termed "in-range chroma reconstruction" by Glenn Chan.
[src:prores-codec/chroma-subsampling] The "proportion" method is in spirit similar to Kornelski's luma-weighted average, while the "spill" method resembles error diffusion.
[src:prores-codec/chroma-subsampling] Improving chroma reconstruction remains an active field of research.
[src:prores-codec/chroma-subsampling] The term Y'UV refers to an analog TV encoding scheme (ITU-R Rec.
[src:prores-codec/chroma-subsampling] BT.470) while Y'CbCr refers to a digital encoding scheme.
[src:prores-codec/chroma-subsampling] One difference between the two is that the scale factors on the chroma components (U, V, Cb, and Cr) are different.
[src:prores-codec/chroma-subsampling] However, the term YUV is often used erroneously to refer to Y'CbCr encoding.
[src:prores-codec/chroma-subsampling] Hence, expressions like "4:2:2 YUV" always refer to 4:2:2 Y'CbCr, since there simply is no such thing as 4:x:x in analog encoding (such as YUV).
[src:prores-codec/chroma-subsampling] Pixel formats used in Y'CbCr can be referred to as YUV too, for example yuv420p, yuvj420p and many others.
[src:prores-codec/chroma-subsampling] In a similar vein, the term luminance and the symbol Y are often used erroneously to refer to luma, which is denoted with the symbol Y'.
[src:prores-codec/chroma-subsampling] The *luma* (Y') of video engineering deviates from the *luminance* (Y) of color science (as defined by CIE).
[src:prores-codec/chroma-subsampling] Luma is formed as the weighted sum of *gamma-corrected* (tristimulus) RGB components.
[src:prores-codec/chroma-subsampling] Luminance is formed as a weighed sum of *linear* (tristimulus) RGB components.
[src:prores-codec/chroma-subsampling] In practice, the CIE symbol Y is often incorrectly used to denote luma.
[src:prores-codec/chroma-subsampling] In 1993, SMPTE adopted Engineering Guideline EG 28, clarifying the two terms.
[src:prores-codec/chroma-subsampling] The prime symbol ' is used to indicate gamma correction.
[src:prores-codec/chroma-subsampling] Similarly, the chroma of video engineering differs from the chrominance of color science.
[src:prores-codec/chroma-subsampling] The chroma of video engineering is formed from weighted tristimulus components (gamma corrected, OETF), not linear components.
[src:prores-codec/chroma-subsampling] In video engineering practice, the terms *chroma*, *chrominance*, and *saturation* are often used interchangeably to refer to chroma, but it is not a good practice, as ITU-T Rec H.273 says.
[src:prores-codec/chroma-subsampling] Chroma subsampling was developed in the 1950s by Alda Bedford for the development of color television by RCA, which developed into the NTSC standard; luma–chroma separation was developed earlier, in 1938 by Georges Valensi.
[src:prores-codec/chroma-subsampling] Through studies, he showed that the human eye has high resolution only for black and white, somewhat less for "mid-range" colors like yellows and greens, and much less for colors on the end of the spectrum, reds and blues.
[src:prores-codec/digital-intermediate] A digital intermediate often replaces or augments the photochemical timing process and is usually the final creative adjustment to a movie before distribution in theaters.
[src:prores-codec/digital-intermediate] It is distinguished from the telecine process in which film is scanned and color is manipulated early in the process to facilitate editing.
[src:prores-codec/digital-intermediate] However the lines between telecine and DI are continually blurred and are often executed on the same hardware by colorists of the same background.
[src:prores-codec/digital-intermediate] These two steps are typically part of the overall color management process in a motion picture at different points in time.
[src:prores-codec/digital-intermediate] A digital intermediate is also customarily done at higher resolution and with greater color fidelity than telecine transfers.
[src:prores-codec/digital-intermediate] This is due to recent advances in digital cinematography and digital projection technologies that strive to match film origination and film projection.
[src:prores-codec/digital-intermediate] In traditional photochemical film finishing, an intermediate is produced by exposing film to the original camera negative.
[src:prores-codec/digital-intermediate] The intermediate is then used to mass-produce the films that get distributed to theaters.
[src:prores-codec/digital-intermediate] Color grading is done by varying the amount of red, green, and blue light used to expose the intermediate.
[src:prores-codec/digital-intermediate] The digital intermediate process uses digital tools to color grade, which allows for much finer control of individual colors and areas of the image, and allows for the adjustment of image structure (grain, sharpness, etc.).
[src:prores-codec/digital-intermediate] The intermediate for film reproduction can then be produced by means of a film recorder.
[src:prores-codec/digital-intermediate] The physical intermediate film that is a result of the recording process is sometimes also called a digital intermediate, and is usually recorded to internegative (IN) stock, which is inherently finer-grain than original camera negative (OCN).
[src:prores-codec/digital-intermediate] One of the key technical achievements that made the transition to DI possible was the use of 3D look-up tables, which could be used to mimic how the digital image would look once it was printed onto release print stock.
[src:prores-codec/digital-intermediate] This removed a large amount of guesswork from the film-making process, and allowed greater freedom in the colour grading process while reducing risk.
[src:prores-codec/digital-intermediate] The digital master is often used as a source for a DCI-compliant distribution of the motion picture for digital projection.
[src:prores-codec/digital-intermediate] For archival purposes, the digital master created during the digital intermediate process can be recorded to very stable high dynamic range yellow-cyan-magenta (YCM) separations on black-and-white film with an expected 100-year or longer life.
[src:prores-codec/digital-intermediate] A "film intermediate" is an analog variation of a digital intermediate, where a project shot on digital video is printed onto film stock and transferred back to digital video to emulate film.
[src:prores-codec/digital-intermediate] The term was coined after it was used on the Oscar-winning 2012 short film "Curfew".
[src:prores-codec/digital-intermediate] The process was also used on the films *Dune* (2021) and *The Batman* (2022).
[src:prores-codec/digital-intermediate] Telecine tools to electronically capture film images are nearly as old as broadcast television, but the resulting images were widely considered unsuitable for exposing back onto film for theatrical distribution.
[src:prores-codec/digital-intermediate] Film scanners and recorders with quality sufficient to produce images that could be inter-cut with regular film began appearing in the 1970s, with significant improvements in the late 1980s and early 1990s.
[src:prores-codec/digital-intermediate] During this time, digitally processing an entire feature-length film was impractical because the scanners and recorders were extremely slow and the image files were too large compared to computing power available.
[src:prores-codec/digital-intermediate] Instead, individual shots or short sequences were processed for visual effects.
[src:prores-codec/digital-intermediate] In 1992, Visual Effects Supervisor/Producer Chris F.
[src:prores-codec/digital-intermediate] Woods broke through several "techno-barriers" in creating a digital studio to produce the visual effects for the 1993 release *Super Mario Bros.* It was the first feature film project to digitally scan a large number of VFX plates (over 700) at 2K resolution.
[src:prores-codec/digital-intermediate] It was also the first film scanned and recorded at Kodak's just launched Cinesite facility in Hollywood.
[src:prores-codec/digital-intermediate] This project based studio was the first feature film to use Discreet Logic's (now Autodesk) Flame and Inferno systems, which enjoyed early dominance as high resolution / high performance digital compositing systems.
[src:prores-codec/digital-intermediate] Digital film compositing for visual effects was immediately embraced, while optical printer use for VFX declined just as quickly.
[src:prores-codec/digital-intermediate] Chris Watts further revolutionized the process on the 1998 feature film *Pleasantville*, becoming the first visual effects supervisor for New Line Cinema to scan, process, and record the majority of a feature-length, live-action, Hollywood film digitally.
[src:prores-codec/digital-intermediate] The first Hollywood film to utilize a digital intermediate process from beginning to end was *O Brother, Where Art Thou?* in 2000 and in Europe it was *Chicken Run* released that same year.
[src:prores-codec/digital-intermediate] The process rapidly caught on in the mid-2000s.
[src:prores-codec/digital-intermediate] Around 50% of Hollywood films went through a digital intermediate in 2005, increasing to around 70% by mid-2007.
[src:prores-codec/digital-intermediate] This is due not only to the extra creative options the process affords film makers but also the need for high-quality scanning and color adjustments to produce movies for digital cinema.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] A **discrete cosine transform** (**DCT**) expresses a finite sequence of data points in terms of a sum of cosine functions oscillating at different frequencies.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] The DCT, first proposed by Nasir Ahmed in 1972, is a widely used transformation technique in signal processing and data compression.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] DCTs are also important to numerous other applications in science and engineering, such as digital signal processing, telecommunication devices, reducing network bandwidth usage, and spectral methods for the numerical solution of partial differential equations.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] A DCT is a Fourier-related transform similar to the discrete Fourier transform (DFT), but using only real numbers.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] The DCTs are generally related to Fourier series coefficients of a periodically and symmetrically extended sequence whereas DFTs are related to Fourier series coefficients of only periodically extended sequences.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] DCTs are equivalent to DFTs of roughly twice the length, operating on real data with even symmetry (since the Fourier transform of a real and even function is real and even), whereas in some variants the input or output data are shifted by half a sample.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] There are eight standard DCT variants, of which four are common.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] The most common variant of discrete cosine transform is the type-II DCT, which is often called simply *the DCT*.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] This was the original DCT as first proposed by Ahmed.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] Its inverse, the type-III DCT, is correspondingly often called simply *the inverse DCT* or *the IDCT*.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] Two related transforms are the discrete sine transform (DST), which is equivalent to a DFT of real and odd functions, and the modified discrete cosine transform (MDCT), which is based on a DCT of overlapping data.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] Multidimensional DCTs (MD DCTs) are developed to extend the concept of DCT to multidimensional signals.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] A variety of fast algorithms have been developed to reduce the computational complexity of implementing DCT.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] One of these is the integer DCT (IntDCT), an integer approximation of the standard DCT, used in several ISO/IEC and ITU-T international standards.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] DCT compression, also known as block compression, compresses data in sets of discrete DCT blocks.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] DCT blocks sizes including 8 × 8 pixels for the standard DCT, and varied integer DCT sizes between 4 × 4 and 32 × 32 pixels.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] The DCT has a strong *energy compaction* property, capable of achieving high quality at high data compression ratios.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] However, blocky compression artifacts can appear when heavy DCT compression is applied.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] The DCT was first conceived by Nasir Ahmed while working at Kansas State University.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] The concept was proposed to the National Science Foundation in 1972.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] The DCT was originally intended for image compression.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] Ahmed developed a practical DCT algorithm with his PhD students T.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] Rao at the University of Texas at Arlington in 1973.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] They presented their results in a January 1974 paper, titled *Discrete Cosine Transform*.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] It described what is now called the type-II DCT (DCT-II), as well as the type-III inverse DCT (IDCT).
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] Since its introduction in 1974, there has been significant research on the DCT.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] In 1977, Wen-Hsiung Chen published a paper with C.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] Fralick presenting a fast DCT algorithm.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] Further developments include a 1978 paper by M.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] These research papers, along with the original 1974 Ahmed paper and the 1977 Chen paper, were cited by the Joint Photographic Experts Group as the basis for JPEG's lossy image compression algorithm in 1992.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] The discrete sine transform (DST) was derived from the DCT, by replacing the Neumann condition at *x=0* with a Dirichlet condition.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] The DST was described in the 1974 DCT paper by Ahmed, Natarajan and Rao.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] A type-I DST (DST-I) was later described by Anil K.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] Jain in 1976, and a type-II DST (DST-II) was then described by H.B.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] Robinson adapted the DCT for inter-frame motion-compensated video coding.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] Jain further developed motion-compensated DCT video compression, also called block motion compensation.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] This led to Chen developing a practical video compression algorithm, called motion-compensated DCT or adaptive scene coding, in 1981.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] Motion-compensated DCT later became the standard coding technique for video compression from the late 1980s onwards.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] A DCT variant, the modified discrete cosine transform (MDCT), was developed by John P.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] Bradley at the University of Surrey in 1987, following earlier work by Princen and Bradley in 1986.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] The MDCT is used in most modern audio compression formats, such as Dolby Digital (AC-3), MP3 (which uses a hybrid DCT-FFT algorithm), Advanced Audio Coding (AAC), and Vorbis (Ogg).
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] Nasir Ahmed also developed a lossless DCT algorithm with Giridhar Mandyam and Neeraj Magotra at the University of New Mexico in 1995.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] This allows the DCT technique to be used for lossless compression of images.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] It is a modification of the original DCT algorithm, and incorporates elements of inverse DCT and delta modulation.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] It is a more effective lossless compression algorithm than entropy coding.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] The DCT is the most widely used transformation technique in signal processing, and by far the most widely used linear transform in data compression.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] DCT compression standards are used in digital media technologies, such as digital images, digital photos, digital video, streaming media, digital television, streaming television, video on demand (VOD), digital cinema, high-definition video (HD video), and high-definition television (HDTV).
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] The DCT, and in particular the DCT-II, is often used in signal and image processing, especially for lossy compression, because it has a strong *energy compaction* property.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] In typical applications, most of the signal information tends to be concentrated in a few low-frequency components of the DCT.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] For strongly correlated Markov processes, the DCT can approach the compaction efficiency of the Karhunen-Loève transform (which is optimal in the decorrelation sense).
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] As explained below, this stems from the boundary conditions implicit in the cosine functions.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] DCTs are widely employed in solving partial differential equations by spectral methods, where the different variants of the DCT correspond to slightly different even and odd boundary conditions at the two ends of the array.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] DCTs are closely related to Chebyshev polynomials, and fast DCT algorithms (below) are used in Chebyshev approximation of arbitrary functions by series of Chebyshev polynomials, for example in Clenshaw–Curtis quadrature.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] The DCT is widely used in many applications, which include the following.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] The DCT-II is an important image compression technique.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] It is used in image compression standards such as JPEG, and video compression standards such as H.26x, MJPEG, MPEG, DV, Theora and Daala.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] There, the two-dimensional DCT-II of $N\times N$ blocks are computed and the results are quantized and entropy coded.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] In this case, N is typically 8 and the DCT-II formula is applied to each row and column of the block.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] The result is an 8 × 8 transform coefficient array in which the $(0,0)$ element (top-left) is the DC (zero-frequency) component and entries with increasing vertical and horizontal index values represent higher vertical and horizontal spatial frequencies.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] The integer DCT, an integer approximation of the DCT, is used in Advanced Video Coding (AVC), introduced in 2003, and High Efficiency Video Coding (HEVC), introduced in 2013.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] The integer DCT is also used in the High Efficiency Image Format (HEIF), which uses a subset of the HEVC video coding format for coding still images.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] HEVC and HEIF use varied block sizes between 4 x 4 and 32 x 32 pixels.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] As of 2019, AVC is by far the most commonly used format for the recording, compression and distribution of video content, used by 91% of video developers, followed by HEVC which is used by 43% of developers.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] Multidimensional DCTs (MD DCTs) have several applications, mainly 3-D DCTs such as the 3-D DCT-II, which has several new applications like Hyperspectral Imaging coding systems, variable temporal length 3-D DCT coding, video coding algorithms, adaptive video coding and 3-D Compression.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] Due to enhancement in the hardware, software and introduction of several fast algorithms, the necessity of using MD DCTs is rapidly increasing.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] DCT-IV has gained popularity for its applications in fast implementation of real-valued polyphase filtering banks, lapped orthogonal transform and cosine-modulated wavelet bases.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] DCT plays an important role in digital signal processing specifically data compression.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] The DCT is widely implemented in digital signal processors (DSP), as well as digital signal processing software.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] Many companies have developed DSPs based on DCT technology.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] DCTs are widely used for applications such as encoding, decoding, video, audio, multiplexing, control signals, signaling, and analog-to-digital conversion.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] DCTs are also commonly used for high-definition television (HDTV) encoder/decoder chips.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] A common issue with DCT compression in digital media are blocky compression artifacts, caused by DCT blocks.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] In a DCT algorithm, an image (or frame in an image sequence) is divided into square blocks which are processed independently from each other, then the DCT blocks is taken within each block and the resulting DCT coefficients are quantized.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] This process can cause blocking artifacts, primarily at high data compression ratios.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] This can also cause the mosquito noise effect, commonly found in digital video.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] DCT blocks are often used in glitch art.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] The artist Rosa Menkman makes use of DCT-based compression artifacts in her glitch art, particularly the DCT blocks found in most digital media formats such as JPEG digital images and MP3 audio.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] Another example is *Jpegs* by German photographer Thomas Ruff, which uses intentional JPEG artifacts as the basis of the picture's style.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] Like any Fourier-related transform, DCTs express a function or a signal in terms of a sum of sinusoids with different frequencies and amplitudes.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] Like the DFT, a DCT operates on a function at a finite number of discrete data points.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] The obvious distinction between a DCT and a DFT is that the former uses only cosine functions, while the latter uses both cosines and sines (in the form of complex exponentials).
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] However, this visible difference is merely a consequence of a deeper distinction: a DCT implies different boundary conditions from the DFT or other related transforms.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] The Fourier-related transforms that operate on a function over a finite domain, such as the DFT or DCT or a Fourier series, can be thought of as implicitly defining an *extension* of that function outside the domain.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] That is, once you write a function $f(x)$ as a sum of sinusoids, you can evaluate that sum at any x , even for x where the original $f(x)$ was not specified.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] The DFT, like the Fourier series, implies a periodic extension of the original function.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] A DCT, like a cosine transform, implies an even extension of the original function.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] However, because DCTs operate on *finite*, *discrete* sequences, two issues arise that do not apply for the continuous cosine transform.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] First, one has to specify whether the function is even or odd at *both* the left and right boundaries of the domain (i.e. the min-*n* and max-*n* boundaries in the definitions below, respectively).
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] Second, one has to specify around *what point* the function is even or odd.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] In particular, consider a sequence *abcd* of four equally spaced data points, and say that we specify an even *left* boundary.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] There are two sensible possibilities: either the data are even about the sample *a*, in which case the even extension is *dcbabcd*, or the data are even about the point *halfway* between *a* and the previous point, in which case the even extension is *dcbaabcd* (*a* is repeated).
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] Each boundary can be either even or odd (2 choices per boundary) and can be symmetric about a data point or the point halfway between two data points (2 choices per boundary), for a total of 2 × 2 × 2 × 2 = 16 possibilities.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] These choices lead to all the standard variations of DCTs and also discrete sine transforms (DSTs).
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] Half of these possibilities, those where the *left* boundary is even, correspond to the 8 types of DCT; the other half are the 8 types of DST.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] These different boundary conditions strongly affect the applications of the transform and lead to uniquely useful properties for the various DCT types.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] Most directly, when using Fourier-related transforms to solve partial differential equations by spectral methods, the boundary conditions are directly specified as a part of the problem being solved.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] Or, for the MDCT (based on the type-IV DCT), the boundary conditions are intimately involved in the MDCT's critical property of time-domain aliasing cancellation.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] In a more subtle fashion, the boundary conditions are responsible for the *energy compactification* properties that make DCTs useful for image and audio compression, because the boundaries affect the rate of convergence of any Fourier-like series.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] In particular, it is well known that any discontinuities in a function reduce the rate of convergence of the Fourier series so that more sinusoids are needed to represent the function with a given accuracy.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] The same principle governs the usefulness of the DFT and other transforms for signal compression; the smoother a function is, the fewer terms in its DFT or DCT are required to represent it accurately, and the more it can be compressed.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] However, the implicit periodicity of the DFT means that discontinuities usually occur at the boundaries: any random segment of a signal is unlikely to have the same value at both the left and right boundaries.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] In contrast, a DCT where *both* boundaries are even *always* yields a continuous extension at the boundaries (although the slope is generally discontinuous).
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] This is why DCTs, and in particular DCTs of types I, II, V, and VI (the types that have two even boundaries) generally perform better for signal compression than DFTs and DSTs.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] In practice, a type-II DCT is usually preferred for such applications, in part for reasons of computational convenience.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] Formally, the discrete cosine transform is a linear, invertible function $f:\mathbb {R} ^{N}\to \mathbb {R} ^{N}$ (where $\mathbb {R}$ denotes the set of real numbers), or equivalently an invertible N × N square matrix.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] There are several variants of the DCT with slightly modified definitions.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] The DCT-I is exactly equivalent (up to an overall scale factor of 2), to a DFT of $2(N-1)$ real numbers with even symmetry.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] For example, a DCT-I of $N=5$ real numbers $a\ b\ c\ d\ e$ is exactly equivalent to a DFT of eight real numbers $a\ b\ c\ d\ e\ d\ c\ b$ (even symmetry), divided by two.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] Note, however, that the DCT-I is not defined for N less than 2, while all other DCT types are defined for any positive N .
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] Thus, the DCT-I corresponds to the boundary conditions: $x_{n}$ is even around $n=0$ and even around $n=N-1$ ; similarly for $X_{k}$ .
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] The DCT-II is probably the most commonly used form, and is often simply referred to as the *DCT*.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] This transform is exactly equivalent (up to an overall scale factor of 2) to a DFT of $4N$ real inputs of even symmetry, where the even-indexed elements are zero.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] DCT-II transformation is also possible using $2N$ signal followed by a multiplication by half shift.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] Some authors further multiply the $X_{0}$ term by $1/{\sqrt {N\,}}\,$ and multiply the rest of the matrix by an overall scale factor of ${\textstyle {\sqrt {{2}/{N}}}}$ (see below for the corresponding change in DCT-III).
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] This makes the DCT-II matrix orthogonal, but breaks the direct correspondence with a real-even DFT of half-shifted input.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] This is the normalization used by Matlab.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] In many applications, such as JPEG, the scaling is arbitrary because scale factors can be combined with a subsequent computational step (e.g. the quantization step in JPEG), and a scaling can be chosen that allows the DCT to be computed with fewer multiplications.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] The DCT-II implies the boundary conditions: $x_{n}$ is even around $n=-1/2$ and even around $n=N-1/2\,$ ; $X_{k}$ is even around $k=0$ and odd around $k=N$ .
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] Because it is the inverse of DCT-II up to a scale factor (see below), this form is sometimes simply referred to as the inverse DCT (IDCT).
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] This makes the DCT-III matrix orthogonal, but breaks the direct correspondence with a real-even DFT of half-shifted output.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] A variant of the DCT-IV, where data from different transforms are *overlapped*, is called the modified discrete cosine transform (MDCT).
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] The DCT-IV implies the boundary conditions: $x_{n}$ is even around $n=-1/2$ and odd around $n=N-1/2$ ; similarly for $X_{k}$ .
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] DCTs of types I–IV treat both boundaries consistently regarding the point of symmetry: they are even or odd around either a data point for both boundaries or halfway between two data points for both boundaries.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] By contrast, DCTs of types V-VIII imply boundaries that are even or odd around a data point for one boundary and halfway between two data points for the other boundary.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] In other words, DCT types I–IV are equivalent to real-even DFTs of even order (regardless of whether N is even or odd), since the corresponding DFT is of length $2(N-1)$ (for DCT-I) or $4N$ (for DCT-II and III) or $8N$ (for DCT-IV).
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] The four additional types of discrete cosine transform correspond essentially to real-even DFTs of logically odd order, which have factors of $N\pm {1}/{2}$ in the denominators of the cosine arguments.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] However, these variants seem to be rarely used in practice.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] One reason, perhaps, is that FFT algorithms for odd-length DFTs are generally more complicated than FFT algorithms for even-length DFTs (e.g., the simplest radix-2 algorithms are only for even lengths), and this increased intricacy carries over to the DCTs as described below.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] Not that the trivial real-even array, a length-one DFT (odd length) of a single number a , corresponds to a DCT-V of length $N=1$ .
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] Using the normalization conventions above, the inverse of DCT-I is DCT-I multiplied by 2/(*N* − 1).
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] The inverse of DCT-IV is DCT-IV multiplied by 2/*N*.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] The inverse of DCT-II is DCT-III multiplied by 2/*N* and vice versa.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] Like for the DFT, the normalization factor in front of these transform definitions is merely a convention and differs between treatments.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] For example, some authors multiply the transforms by ${\textstyle {\sqrt {2/N}}}$ so that the inverse does not require any additional multiplicative factor.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] Combined with appropriate factors of √2 (see above), this can be used to make the transform matrix orthogonal.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] Multidimensional variants of the various DCT types follow straightforwardly from the one-dimensional definitions: they are simply a separable product (equivalently, a composition) of DCTs along each dimension.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] For example, a two-dimensional DCT-II of an image or a matrix is simply the one-dimensional DCT-II, from above, performed along the rows and then along the columns (or vice versa).
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] The inverse of a multi-dimensional DCT is just a separable product of the inverses of the corresponding one-dimensional DCTs (see above), e.g., the one-dimensional inverses applied along one dimension at a time in a row-column algorithm.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] Technically, computing a two-, three- (or -multi) dimensional DCT by sequences of one-dimensional DCTs along each dimension is known as a *row-column* algorithm.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] As with multidimensional FFT algorithms, however, there exist other methods to compute the same thing while performing the computations in a different order (i.e., interleaving or combining the algorithms for the different dimensions).
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] Owing to the rapid growth in the applications based on the 3-D DCT, several fast algorithms have been developed for the computation of 3-D DCT-II.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] Vector-Radix algorithms are applied for computing M-D DCT to reduce the computational complexity and to increase the computational speed.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] Vector-Radix Decimation in Frequency (VR DIF) is an example of an algorithm to compute a 3-D DCT-II efficiently.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] In order to apply the VR DIF algorithm, the input data must be formulated and rearranged as follows.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] The transform size *N × N × N* is assumed to be 2.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] The adjacent figure shows the four stages that are involved in calculating 3-D DCT-II using VR DIF algorithm.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] The first stage is the 3-D reordering using the index mapping illustrated by the above equations.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] The second stage is the butterfly calculation.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] Each butterfly calculates eight points together as shown in the figure just below, where $c(\varphi _{i})=\cos(\varphi _{i})$ .
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] The whole 3-D DCT calculation needs $~[\log _{2}N]~$ stages, and each stage involves $~{\tfrac {1}{8}}\ N^{3}~$ butterflies.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] Each butterfly requires seven real multiplications (including trivial multiplications) and 24 real additions (including trivial additions).
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] The conventional method to calculate MD-DCT-II is using a Row-Column-Frame (RCF) approach, which is computationally complex and less productive on most recent advanced hardware platforms.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] The VR DIF algorithm requires fewer multiplications than the RCF algorithm.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] The total number of multiplications associated with the 3-D DCT VR algorithm is less than that associated with the RCF approach by more than 40%.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] In addition, the RCF approach involves matrix transpose and more indexing and data swapping than the VR DIF algorithm.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] This makes the 3-D DCT VR algorithm more efficient and better suited for 3-D applications that involve the 3-D DCT-II, such as video compression and other 3-D image processing applications.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] The main consideration in choosing a fast algorithm is to avoid computational and structural complexities.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] As the technology of computers and DSPs advances, the execution time of arithmetic operations (multiplications and additions) improves and regular computational structure becomes the most important factor.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] Therefore, although the above proposed 3-D VR algorithm does not achieve the theoretical lower bound on the number of multiplications, it has a simpler computational structure as compared to other 3-D DCT algorithms.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] It can be implemented in place using a single butterfly and possesses the properties of the Cooley–Tukey FFT algorithm in 3-D.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] Hence, the 3-D VR presents a good choice for reducing arithmetic operations in the calculation of the 3-D DCT-II, while keeping the simple structure that characterizes butterfly-style Cooley–Tukey FFT algorithms.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] The image to the right shows a combination of horizontal and vertical frequencies for an 8 × 8 $(~N_{1}=N_{2}=8~)$ two-dimensional DCT.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] Each step from left to right and top to bottom is an increase in frequency by a half-cycle.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] For example, moving right one from the top-left square yields a half-cycle increase in the horizontal frequency.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] Another move to the right yields two half-cycles.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] A move down yields two half-cycles horizontally and a half-cycle vertically.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] The source data (8 × 8) is transformed to a linear combination of these 64 frequency squares.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] The MD DCT-IV is an extension of 1-D DCT-IV onto an M-dimensional domain.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] We can compute the MD DCT-IV using the regular row-column method, or we can use the polynomial transform method for fast and efficient computation.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] The main idea of this algorithm is to use the polynomial transform to directly convert the multidimensional DCT into a series of 1-D DCTs.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] Although the direct application of these formulas would require $~{\mathcal {O}}(N^{2})~$ operations, it is possible to compute the same thing with only $~{\mathcal {O}}(N\log N)~$ complexity by factorizing the computation similarly to the fast Fourier transform (FFT).
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] One can also compute DCTs via FFTs combined with $~{\mathcal {O}}(N)~$ pre- and post-processing steps.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] In general, $~{\mathcal {O}}(N\log N)~$ methods to compute DCTs are known as fast cosine transform (FCT) algorithms.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] The most efficient algorithms, in principle, are usually those that are specialized directly for the DCT, as opposed to using an ordinary FFT plus $~{\mathcal {O}}(N)~$ extra operations (see below for an exception).
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] This can even be done automatically (Frigo & Johnson 2005).
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] Algorithms based on the Cooley–Tukey FFT algorithm are most common, but any other FFT algorithm is also applicable.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] For example, the Winograd FFT algorithm leads to minimal-multiplication algorithms for the DFT, albeit generally at the cost of more additions, and a similar algorithm was proposed by (Feig & Winograd 1992a) for the DCT.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] Because the algorithms for DFTs, DCTs, and similar transforms are all so closely related, any improvement in algorithms for one transform will theoretically lead to immediate gains for the other transforms as well (Duhamel & Vetterli 1990).
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] While DCT algorithms that employ an unmodified FFT often have some theoretical overhead compared to the best specialized DCT algorithms, the former also have a distinct advantage: Highly optimized FFT programs are widely available.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] Thus, in practice, it is often easier to obtain high performance for general lengths N with FFT-based algorithms.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] Specialized DCT algorithms, on the other hand, see widespread use for transforms of small, fixed sizes such as the 8 × 8 DCT-II used in JPEG compression, or the small DCTs (or MDCTs) typically used in audio compression.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] In fact, even the DCT algorithms using an ordinary FFT are sometimes equivalent to pruning the redundant operations from a larger FFT of real-symmetric data, and they can even be optimal from the perspective of arithmetic counts.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] For example, a type-II DCT is equivalent to a DFT of size $~4N~$ with real-even symmetry whose even-indexed elements are zero.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] Because the even-indexed elements are zero, this radix-4 step is exactly the same as a split-radix step.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] If the subsequent size $~N~$ real-data FFT is also performed by a real-data split-radix algorithm (as in Sorensen et al.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] (1987)), then the resulting algorithm actually matches what was long the lowest published arithmetic count for the power-of-two DCT-II ( $~2N\log _{2}N-N+2~$ real-arithmetic operations).
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] A recent reduction in the operation count to $~{\tfrac {17}{9}}N\log _{2}N+{\mathcal {O}}(N)$ also uses a real-data FFT.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] So, there is nothing intrinsically bad about computing the DCT via an FFT from an arithmetic perspective – it is sometimes merely a question of whether the corresponding FFT algorithm is optimal.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] Consider this 8 × 8 grayscale image of capital letter A.
[src:prores-codec/discrete-cosine-transform] Each basis function is multiplied by its coefficient and then this product is added to the final image.
[src:prores-codec/intra-frame-coding] Intra-frame prediction exploits spatial redundancy, i.e. correlation among pixels within one frame, by calculating prediction values through extrapolation from already coded pixels for effective delta coding.
[src:prores-codec/intra-frame-coding] It is one of the two classes of predictive coding methods in video coding.
[src:prores-codec/intra-frame-coding] Its counterpart is inter-frame prediction which exploits temporal redundancy.
[src:prores-codec/intra-frame-coding] Temporally independently coded so-called intra frames use only intra coding.
[src:prores-codec/intra-frame-coding] The temporally coded predicted frames (e.g.
[src:prores-codec/intra-frame-coding] MPEG's P- and B-frames) may use intra- as well as inter-frame prediction.
[src:prores-codec/intra-frame-coding] Usually only few of the spatially closest known samples are used for the extrapolation.
[src:prores-codec/intra-frame-coding] Formats that operate sample by sample like Portable Network Graphics (PNG) can usually use one of four adjacent pixels (above, above left, above right, left) or some function of them like e.g. their average.
[src:prores-codec/intra-frame-coding] Block-based (frequency transform) formats prefill whole blocks with prediction values extrapolated from usually one or two straight lines of pixels that run along their top and left borders.
[src:prores-codec/intra-frame-coding] Inter frame has been specified by the CCITT in 1988–1990 by H.261 for the first time.
[src:prores-codec/intra-frame-coding] H.261 was meant for teleconferencing and ISDN telephoning.
[src:prores-codec/intra-frame-coding] Data is usually read from a video camera or a video card in the YCbCr data format (often informally called YUV for brevity).
[src:prores-codec/intra-frame-coding] The coding process varies greatly depending on which type of encoder is used (e.g., JPEG or H.264), but the most common steps usually include: partitioning into macroblocks, transformation (e.g., using a DCT or wavelet), quantization and entropy encoding.
[src:prores-codec/intra-frame-coding] It is used in codecs like ProRes: a group of pictures codec without inter frames.
